6 quin etiam: Only here and Ann. XII 61 quin etiam dixit, ‘ quin et' being elsewhere preferred by Tacitus.

7 probitati · · · modestiae: On this common collocation, see crit. note c. 5 1.—parvulos=infantes, if we except Caes. B. G. VI 21 a parvulis ¹ from early childhood,' seems not to occur in pre- Augustan writers. It is rare in Silver Latin (e. g. Val. Max. II 6, 16 Quint. 1 1, 24 V 7, 36 Plin. Pan. 26), occurs once in Fronto, Florus, Apuleius and Censorinus, and a number of times in Ps. Quint. Declam. The Church Fathers appropriated the word, clearly distinguishing it from ‘infantes’ Cf. e. g. Augustin. M. XXXIV 416, 5 parentes cum parvulis et infantibus. Strange to say, the term never occurs on inscriptions. Cp. the exhaustive discussion of Funk, Archiv VII 73-102. — non· · · neque· · · sed: An exceed- ingly common correlation in Tacitus. Cf. c. 12 3 19 4 21 34 25 28 29 17 31 2 36 30 Ag. 19. 33 G. 7 (twice) 11. 18 H. I 38. 43 III 38 Ann. I 31. 68 IV 62 XII 10 XVI 2. ‘non in place of ‘neque' (neo) imparts additional emphasis. Cp. Dr. H. S. I 85 R. V. III 218 f. notes 414ο 415.

8 lasciviae et dicacitati: Lascivia in a bad sense is chiefly post- Aug. and not yet found in Cicero, but in Tacitus, with three excep- tions (G. 24 H. II 68 Ann. XI 31), out of 32 instances, it is always so used.-Dz·cacitas ‘banter’ is also used in bonam partem by Cicero e. g. de orat. II 54, 219 ff. Orat. 26, 87 and by Quint. VI 3, 21 who derives the word from ‘dicere’ and defines it as 'sermonem cum risu aliquos incessentem. Both terms are combined by Quint. VI 3, 41 Siculi quidem ut sunt lascivi et dicaces.
